If I write omniscient narrator I tend to get a little prolix and lost tbh. For some reason POV writing for me works better to make the character being understood AND empathized, and also show how they can be wrong in some stuff they think.

I realized I really like to explore the characters inner thoughts and how they're Actually Feeling about everything around them instead of doing stuff that just describes what's happening. POV writing instead of omniscient narrator ftw!!

He despised the way Shen Yuan said his name.

And yet that same man had been in his arms. That one felt real, a solid weight on him. He didn’t know how to feel about this. He wanted to ask about Liu Qingge more, but he didn’t want to hear it from Shen Yuan.

The Liu Qingge Shen Yuan spoke of was his admirable love rival. He was so perfect, so cool, so talented, so… distant.

It felt like Luo Binghe was fighting a straw man in the shape of Liu Qingge. He hated him, wanted to make Shen Yuan forget about him completely.

It made Luo Binghe slightly annoyed. He didn’t know if it was because he /still/ couldn’t get Shen Yuan’s full attention for himself, or if it was because the version of Liu Qingge that Shen Yuan was always talking about wasn’t something he had actually met.

Every time he went out with Shen Yuan, Liu Qingge ended up being a topic somehow. He knew part of it was because he wanted them together, but little by little he also realized it was just because Shen Yuan liked him so much.

I’d never be as good as Qingge with the bass itself, he’d be much more insightful for you than me.”

Luo Binghe’s smile waned a little.

Luo Binghe answered, walking along Shen Yuan to the cafeteria on the corner of the street, bass case on his back.

Shen Yuan waved his hand. “My major just happens to be a topic I can share with you, it’s not like I can be of much use besides this.

“Ah, but isn’t Yuan-ge worthy of admiration as well? You might like my bass skills, but any time we’re talking about music you have such great insights, and you also know so much. I can’t help but be your fan, too.”
“You know you can call me anytime. If I’m free, I can meet you. But talking like that… feels like I’m the idol here, it’s a bit embarrassing.”

Shen Yuan giggled, patting his head. It had become a habit once he found out about Luo Binghe’s cute side - at first it was on impulse, but once Luo Binghe gave him his best smile in response, it seemed to unlock something in Shen Yuan, so he did it all the time now.

“Hey Binghe. I’m sorry this is going to be quick, but since I was around I thought we could grab some coffee...”  

“Of course. Any time I can spend with Yuan-ge is good enough for me.”

--- 

Shen Yuan’s smile was radiant when Luo Binghe arrived at their meeting spot. He couldn’t hide his excitement to meet his Yuan-ge in person once again, and smiled back at him.

“I know you just want to be nosy. Poor thing might not survive you if he meets you in person.”

He shrugged, adorably (and irritatingly) showing his tongue. “I’m just protective of my kids. C’mon, let’s play.”

“Pfft. Fine then,” he scoffed. “Bring your nerdy twink over for one of our sessions. He’s a fan, isn’t he? Bet he’d like to have a little concert specially for him.”

Luo Binghe side-eyed Shang Qinghua and shook his head, pinching one of his soft cheeks.

Shang Qinghua rolled his eyes. “Whatever, bro. If you’re this invested I’m not stopping you, but know you /are/ going to be hurt. That’s not something leading to a happy ending.” 

“I still think it’s worth a try,” he answered, resolute, and Shang Qinghua raised his eyebrows.

“Why the fuck would you willingly hold a hot potato like that? Pass it over, it’s not your problem to deal with.”

Luo Binghe looked at his messages with Shen Yuan again, seeing the small thumbnails for all the photos and videos they exchanged, still not saying anything.

Luo Binghe looked at him, sighing. “It’s… complicated.”

“Closeted?” Shang Qinghua asked, but Luo Binghe remained silent, which he knew Shang Qinghua would read as an affirmative answer.

“You don’t even know him to be saying that.” Luo Binghe frowned, slightly annoyed.

Shang Qinghua scoffed. “Do I really need to, though? You’ve been talking for almost two months and have yet to even kiss. I call that lame,” he shrugged.

Luo Binghe opened the message to read, not caring if Shang Qinghua would read it as well. “You say that as if you’re not a nerd yourself.”

“The difference is that he’s lame and I’m cool,” Shang Qinghua flashed a smile, winking.

Luo Binghe looked at him with a serious expression, and started strumming his bass’ strings, experimenting, and Sha Hualing started singing along with the rhythm; soon Mobei Jun joined them, and suddenly they had the chorus for their new song, only lacking the guitar part.

“I told you to stop calling me that,” he answered, though not making her move away from him. “Qinghua, what’s wrong with her lyrics?”
Sha Hualing, however, immediately jumped on him, clinging onto his neck, her pouting deepening. “JUNSHANG! Qinghua didn’t approve of my new lyrics, tell him off for me!”
“Yo,” he said faintly, taking his bass out of the case and plugging it in the amplifier, trying not to disturb them too much.

When Luo Binghe arrived at the studio, all of the other members of Endless Abyss were already there. Shang Qinghua and Mobei Jun were concentrating on discussing how their parts would go along in their new song, while Sha Hualing was pouting in the corner.

Resting his head on his arm, Shen Yuan's around him, the faint light illuminating Shen Yuan's soft features, Liu Qingge finally fell asleep as it should be; looking at the one to whom his heart had always belonged.

His nose was marked all over because of his crooked glasses that were pressed against it, and Liu Qingge took them off slowly, even though he knew that at this rate he was sleeping so deeply it would take an earthquake to wake him up.

Shen Yuan's plushy lips were partially open and Liu Qingge could see he was drooling a little. The dimples were more evident when he smiled, but the very small indentation on his cheeks were there and it took all his strength to not kiss them right there and then.

It took a moment or two for him to even out his breathing and calm the wild thrumming inside his chest, and then finally be able to focus on the sleeping face is front of him.

The lights were mostly out, but it was still enough for him to drink in the details of it.

He didn't know if that was a mistake or what - when he settled in his new position, he realized just how /close/ he was from Shen Yuan's face. Their noses were almost touching and he could feel Shen Yuan's breath on him.

He wanted to intertwine their fingers, press himself back against him, turn around and kiss him awake, bring him to bed and sleep and wake up holding him in his arms, every day of his life.

He halted once he felt SY shifting a bit in his sleep, but he stopped right after, soft snores back and filling the now silent living room.

LQG stared at a dark corner near the TV hack, just feeling Shen Yuan’s presence for a while, their hands fitting perfectly over each other.

But he didn’t realize in time to stop himself, that he was moving his hand towards Shen Yuan’s. Just before reaching it, he hovered over it a little, but ended up giving in. He closed his eyes and squeezed his hand ever so slightly, rubbing his thumb over one of his knuckles.

like if they were riding his bike and Shen Yuan should hold him for safety - they were just… snuggling.

When the credits started to roll up the screen, Liu Qingge turned off the TV. He stayed in the same position for a while, trying so hard to just… think nothing of it.

Shen Yuan’s arm was firmly keeping him close. He could feel Shen Yuan’s body heat across all his back now, the back of his thighs being touched by the bony structure of Shen Yuan’s. They were impossibly close, and there wasn’t any practical reason for that, +

his glasses crooked and lips partially open - indicating he was just lightly asleep, otherwise he would be roaring through the room with his snores.
